<subSubSection id="C68BC180457EFFB48DA1A111FD69FD9B" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="1264" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" type="description">
<paragraph id="8E2E920B457EFFB58DA1A111FE97FB2D" blockId="6.[151,1059,1023,1162]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">
D i a g n o s i s: 
<taxonomicName id="4991E988457EFFB58C6DA111FE07FBB3" authority="Schmid, 2021" authorityName="Schmid" authorityYear="2021" box="[347,511,1023,1045]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Belomicrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heinrichwolfi" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="BCE54E19457EFFB58C6DA111FE07FBB3" box="[347,511,1023,1045]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">B. heinrichwolfi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A7D6F362457EFFB58F31A111FDA9FBB2" box="[519,593,1024,1045]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4991E988457EFFB58FEFA111FC9AFBB3" authority="Schmid, 2021" authorityName="Schmid" authorityYear="2021" box="[729,866,1023,1045]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Belomicrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="christmani" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="BCE54E19457EFFB58FEFA111FC9AFBB3" box="[729,866,1023,1045]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">B. christmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A7D6F362457EFFB58E5CA111FC4EFBB2" box="[874,950,1024,1045]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, described from 
<collectingCountry id="F686D29B457EFFB58DF8A10CFED5FB95" box="[206,301,1053,1074]" name="Morocco" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">Morocco</collectingCountry>
. Both species share a special and unique form of the squamae (
<figureCitation id="16AA8E8E457EFFB58E94A10CFC21FB94" box="[930,985,1053,1075]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[151,191,1444,1466]" captionTargetBox="[155,1062,200,1434]" captionTargetId="figure-65@4.[155,1062,200,1434]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Squamae and mucro. (1) Belomicrus atlasiensis nov.sp. ♂, (2) Belomicrus christmani nov.sp. ♀, (3) Belomicrus dunensis ♀ from Morocco, (4) Belomicrus heinrichwolfi nov.sp. ♂, (5) Belomicrus italicus ♀ from Sicily, (6) Belomicrus odontophorus ♀ from Morocco, (7) Belomicrus rasmonti nov.sp. ♀, (8) Oxybelomorpha maroccana ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5038974" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5038974/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">fig. 4</figureCitation>
). It has a deep, U-shaped emargination apically. Both species differ by the surface of the squamae, which is distinctly shiny in 
<taxonomicName id="4991E988457EFFB58C9BA149FDA8FBCB" authority="Schmid, 2021" authorityName="Schmid" authorityYear="2021" box="[429,592,1111,1133]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Belomicrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heinrichwolfi" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="BCE54E19457EFFB58C9BA149FDA8FBCB" box="[429,592,1111,1133]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">B. heinrichwolfi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A7D6F362457EFFB58F60A149FD58FBCA" box="[598,672,1112,1133]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and with some striae and more dull in 
<taxonomicName id="4991E988457EFFB58DA1A164FED8FB2D" authority="Schmid, 2021" authorityName="Schmid" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,288,1141,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Belomicrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="christmani" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="BCE54E19457EFFB58DA1A164FED8FB2D" box="[151,288,1141,1162]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">B. christmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A7D6F362457EFFB58C10A164FE97FB2D" box="[294,367,1141,1162]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E2E920B457EFFB48DA1A18AFEA1FE73" blockId="6.[151,1059,1178,1581]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1059,211,468]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="1264" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">
D e s c r i p t i o n o f m a l e h o l o t y p e: Body length 
<quantity id="49693FEE457EFFB58E04A18BFC7AFB17" box="[818,898,1178,1200]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
. Colour: Black, with the following parts yellow: basal half of mandible (apex black), scape (with brown band above), flagellomeres below, pronotal lobe, margin of squamae, apex of femora, tibiae and tarsi, apex of tergite VI. Tegula and basal sclerite of forwing transparent with some reddish parts, basal veins of forewing reddish, remaining veins dark brown. Wings transparent. Apical margin of tergites reddish. Morphology: Ventral mandibular margin straight. Apical clypeal margin weakly tridentate, lateral corner black, medial point with obtse angle, reddish (
<figureCitation id="16AA8E8E457EFFB58C43A076FE44FADA" box="[373,444,1383,1405]" captionStart="Figs 15-18" captionStartId="6.[151,191,839,861]" captionTargetBox="[154,1061,217,830]" captionTargetId="figure-355@6.[154,1061,217,830]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 15-18: (15) Oxybelomorpha maroccana ♀ from Morocco habitus lateral; (16) Oxybelomorpha stecki ♀ from Spain habitus lateral; (17) Belomicrus atlasiensis nov.sp. ♂ clypeus; (18) Belomicrus heinrichwolfi nov.sp. ♂ clypeus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5038978" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5038978/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">fig. 18</figureCitation>
). Clypeus shiny below. Gena shiny below near mandibular socket, frons also shiny above scape, remaining head and mesopleuron punctato-striate, mesonotum and scutellum densely punctured, interspaces shiny. 
<collectingCountry id="F686D29B457EFFB58E1FA0B3FCB1FA10" box="[809,841,1442,1463]" name="American Samoa" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">AS</collectingCountry>
2-12 appr. as long as wide, 
<collectingCountry id="F686D29B457EFFB58DE2A0AEFF0EFA73" box="[212,246,1471,1492]" name="American Samoa" pageId="6" pageNumber="1263">AS</collectingCountry>
13 twice as long as basally wide. OOL = ocellar diameter, between lateral ocellus and eye with orbital fovea. Vertex large, distance between hindocellus and hindmargin of vertex as long as length of scape. Pronotal collar with indistinct medial impression. Mesopleuron below and mesosternum without carinae, mesopleuron in front of midcoxa with shiny lamella, twice as long as high, and as high as midocellar diameter. Squamae shiny, apically with deep U-shaped emargination, lateral margin bent upwards. Mucro apically enlarged, apex as large as wide of emargination of squamae (
<figureCitation id="16AA8E8E457FFFB48E60A41FFC62FE83" box="[854,922,270,292]" captionStart="Figs 9-14" captionStartId="5.[151,191,1144,1166]" captionTargetBox="[153,1060,209,1133]" captionTargetId="figure-210@5.[153,1060,209,1133]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 9-14: (9) Belomicrus atlasiensis nov.sp. ♂ habitus lateral; (10) Belomicrus christmani nov.sp. ♀ habitus lateral; (11) Belomicrus heinrichwolfi nov.sp. ♂ habitus lateral; (12) Belomicrus italicus ♀ from Sicily, habitus lateral; (13) Belomicrus odontophorus ♀ from Morocco, habitus lateral; (14) Belomicrus rasmonti nov.sp. ♀ habitus lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5038976" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5038976/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1264">fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Propodeum dull, with fine reticulation and some striae, laterally in whole length horizontally striated. Tergites I-V dull, finely and densely punctured, punctures half in size compared to punctures of mesosoma. Tergite VI shiny with large punctation. All tergites laterally with keel in whole length. Sternites with indistinct and fine punctation, shiny, with a few erect pale setae. Lower half of face covered with short silver pubescence, remaining body with sparse pubescence.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E2E920B457FFFB48DA1A4F2FC44FE5E" blockId="7.[151,956,483,505]" box="[151,956,483,505]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1264">
G e o g r a f i c d i s t r i b u t i o n: Alicancte province in southern 
<collectingCountry id="F686D29B457FFFB48E4DA4F2FC40FE5E" box="[891,952,483,505]" name="Spain" pageId="7" pageNumber="1264">Spain</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8E2E920B457FFFB48DA1A718FD69FD9B" blockId="7.[151,1058,520,572]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1264">
E t y m o l o g y: The species is named in honour to the late Heinrich Wolf, a leading expert of 
<taxonomicName id="4991E988457FFFB48DCEA737FE96FD9B" box="[248,366,550,572]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pompilidae</taxonomicName>
, who collected the 
<typeStatus id="512A2CA9457FFFB48F07A737FD75FD9B" box="[561,653,550,572]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1264">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
